>>30178918
The core of what made the comic good was its strange combination of themes. It's probably the bleakest dystopian post-apocalypse I've seen in terms of execution. The representation of the wasteland as nothing but a monochrome, flat plain is pretty haunting. The barely functioning, insanely authoritarian survivor society and the barely even human anymore actual human survivors works well. The weird transformation body horror works. And then it's all combined with these saturday morning cartoon aesthetics in a way that somehow accentuates just how fucked up everything is.

And most of it is held together by interesting, believable characters. And that's where the buck stops for me, I think, after the Holly arc. Because ultimately that was the glue of the comic. There were some cracks here and there, but the thing that made that weird world work is that everyone seemed to be in on it. These people knew they were cartoon animals, and they tried to deal with that. And that's what I hate about whats-her-face, the lizard girl. She doesn't fit. He canonically makes her too dumb to understand the horrors she's seeing. And then the arc after that was too boring for me to fully read, so I don't know. I might go back one day and confirm if I'm right about this, but I usually am.

As for other webcomics, I read Out of Placers because it was shilled on /co/ and I actually like it. I also read Unsounded, and I think it's legit one of the best comics available in any format today. Yesterday I found Ten Earthshattering Blows. It's decent. It's helped by having a main character that's right up me fetish alley. Finished Mare Internum a few weeks ago. It's OK, not the best, but it's complete. I used to read boatloads of webcomics when I was younger, but so so many are just bad, and so so many have pacing issues, and so so many get dropped abruptly.

Frankly, one reason I think Unsounded is unique is because the author is far more disciplined than other webcomic authors.
